description:
Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) significantly improve the performance of complex tasks by generating long-chain reasoning, but their reasoning process suffers from redundant paths, ineffective expansions, and exponentially increasing computational overhead. Existing methods mostly rely on heuristic pruning or external control, lacking a theoretical characterization of the reasoning structure itself.  
 &nbsp; 
  This paper proposes a novel training paradigm&mdash;Polytope-Constrained Reasoning (PCR). This method, starting from polyhedral combination theory, models the reasoning process as a feasible path search problem within a high-dimensional polyhedron, where:  
 &nbsp; 
  Each reasoning chain corresponds to a point (or path).  
 &nbsp; 
  A set of reasonable reasoning statements constitutes a convex polyhedron.  
 &nbsp; 
  Redundant reasoning corresponds to the exterior of the polyhedron or non-extreme regions.  
 &nbsp; 
  Optimal reasoning corresponds to extreme points or low-dimensional faces.  
 &nbsp; 
  We propose:  
 &nbsp; 
  1) Reasoning Polyhedron Construction  
 &nbsp; 
  2) Cutting-Plane Guided Training  
 &nbsp; 
  3) Extreme Point Sparsification  
 &nbsp; 
  4) Extended Formulation Compression  
 &nbsp; 
  This paradigm transforms the model from "generating token sequences" to "searching for the optimal structural path within the polyhedron," thus theoretically unifying reasoning efficiency and correctness.

